label chapter3:

    # [Scene: Your Small Office above the Promenade | Late Night → Pre-dawn]

    scene bg ch3_98c6f2_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rain against corrugated awnings; distant, steady thump of the sea on stilts]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low, pulsing drone — quiet, inscrutable]
    "You fold the tablet again because your hands need the motion. The device feels heavier than when you closed it in the council chamber; the weight is not silicon and glass but the shape of decisions"
    "that haven't been made yet. On the screen a leaked PDF scrolls in your memory: a consortium amendment, language sharpened like a blade—accelerated timelines, “asset reset” phrasing folded into legalese, clauses that could justify relocating entire"
    "low-lying blocks under the guise of efficiency."
    "Your brass tide-line pendant presses warm against your sternum as if trying to point you away from the shore. It doesn't. It spins, not with the ease of a compass but with a frantic insistence that makes your chest tighten."

    "You read the sentences again in the dark. Each line feels like a measurement you already failed to take" "expedited procurement,' 'foreseeable asset consolidation,' 'contingent eminent domain."
    "Memory comes like cold spray. You are back on a gravel street with sandbags in your arms, the night a sheaf of rain, the generator's breath rasping in the alley. Neighbors—names you have not said aloud"
    "in months—calling for help you couldn't give fast enough. A child's small hand under a soaked blanket. You had mapped the storm then and failed to turn the curve. The guilt is a tide you wear."

    scene bg ch3_98c6f2_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A muted ringtone, then voicemail click]
    show asha_karim at left:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_karim "Maya. Listen—meet me at the Old Beacon. Bring nothing but yourself. Do not let this go quiet."
    "Her tone is the worn cord in a bell—urgent but composed."
    "Your phone buzzes again with a flurry: Emil Kwon's name, then Diego's group chat lighting up with a photo you already know will be everywhere—Noah Ortega at a press podium, lapel pin gleaming, headlines framing the"
    "amendment as 'necessary protection.' Mayor Chen's feed flashes: emergency session called. A city that smells of wet rope and antiseptic is turning toward a single, sharp decision."
    "You stand. The room is small and smells of damp paper and coffee cooling at the rim. Outside the promenade is a river of market lights and tarps, water kissing pilings like a repetitive question."
    # [Scene Transition: Down the Stair, Into the Rain]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Wooden steps creak; boots slap wet boards; a loose tarp flaps above the market like a tired banner]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A minor piano line joins the drone — steady, insistent]
    # [Scene: Tideward Promenade | Morning — Rain-dark Canopies]
    hide asha_karim

    scene bg ch3_98c6f2_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Water slapping against pontoons; distant generator; voices muffled by tarps]
    # [Smell: Salted fish, wet canvas, warm bread wrapped in greaseproof paper]
    "Emil Kwon is there before you fully cross the main boardwalk. He stands with his hands thrust into the pockets of his patched canvas, shoulders squared as if bracing for a wind that isn't only meteorological."
    "Sea-glass eyes find you and hold—wet, rimmed in the same gray as the sky, but steady."
    show emil_kwon at left:
        zoom 0.7

    emil_kwon "You saw it."
    "He doesn't wait for a reply; his voice is a low current."
    "You nod. You don't have to say the words; the amendment lives under the skin of the morning."
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "The clauses are worse than the rumor. They don't just speed things up—they re-title assets under contingency. It's a legal shutter."
    "Emil Kwon's jaw tightens. He pulls a flyer from his satchel and hands it to a woman nailing a patch on a tarpaulin: bold letters—'NO DISPLACEMENT.' His face is an open map of contained anger."

    emil_kwon "They'll call it triage. They'll call it efficient. They'll call the people 'collateral.' I won't let them call our neighbors that."
    "He exhales, a small, fierce sound."
    "Diego Ramos materializes from beneath a canopy, armfuls of flyers, rain beading on his shoulders. He breathes in and out like a man used to shouting over crowds."
    show diego_ramos at center:
        zoom 0.7

    diego_ramos "We got the leak out on the boards an hour ago. People are pissed. People are scared. If the vote goes like that, my cousin's block—gone. Told them to meet at the community hall tonight."
    "He spreads a map with trembling fingers."
    "You study the map. Asteria's coastal lab, the Promenade, Old Beacon: pins like bruises on a city you love."

    maya_reyes "Mayor Chen called an emergency session. Noah Ortega's face is already in the headlines with that pin."
    "You make a small gesture, half laugh, half curse. 'He's framing it as necessary protection.'"

    emil_kwon "Of course he is. It's what he does—sells the idea of safety while clearing the decks."
    "He looks down at his hands, then up at you. 'Maya, what do you want to do?'"
    "Your throat tightens. The options collect like stormclouds you can map but can't disperse: negotiate amendments at the council table, stand visibly with Emil Kwon and the makers in street resistance, or dig for the consortium's"
    "strings and expose them. Each is a different kind of exposure—public bargaining, public defiance, or surgical public unmasking."
    "Diego Ramos leans in, voice low and urgent."

    diego_ramos "We can stand at the Hall tonight. Make it loud. Make them see the faces. If people show up—if we break their veneer—maybe they stall."
    "He slams a damp palm on the map. 'We have to make it political, not just technical.'"
    "Your mind runs through protocol, calibrations, projections. Negotiations can be precise; they can also make compromises that look like protections and feel like betrayals. Resistance can hold people together, but can it stop bulldozers and bonds?"
    "Investigation can root out rot, but it takes time—time the council says they don't have."

    menu:
        "Hand out flyers with Diego":
            "You slip into the crowd, the paper cool and wet in your palm. Diego nods and hands you a stack; people take them with hands that shake. Your voice—when you raise it—is steady, brittle with anger, and someone meets your eyes and doesn't look away."
        "Call Asha and tell her you'll meet at the Old Beacon":
            "You dial fast. Asha Karim answers on the second ring. You leave your location terse and exact; she replies with a sharp promise to wait—her 'do not let this go quiet' hangs between you. The call closes with the sound of her coat zipper."
        "Confront Noah publicly on his feed — post the amendment and name the clause":
            "You type for ten seconds and then delete. Your thumb hovers. You post anyway: the excerpt, the image of the clause. Notifications explode — some supportive, some accusing you of theatrics. Noah Ortega's office issues a denial within the hour. The pin in the photos gleams under studio lights."

    menu:
        "Promise to negotiate from inside—tell them you'll talk to the Mayor":
            "You pull out your tablet and draft a terse message to the Mayor's office. You mention amendments, safeguards. Emil Kwon watches you—his jaw softens but his eyes narrow with worry."
        "Stand with Emil and pledge to be at the Hall tonight":
            "You reach across the damp table and grip Emil Kwon's sleeve. Your voice is low, thick. He smiles a small, broken smile and pulls you close for an instant—enough to promise not comfort, but solidarity."

